LMG Mixed‐Use Development Planning Level Traffic Impact Analysis
Graham Associates has retained Savant Group, Inc. (SGI) to prepare a planning level traffic
impact analysis (PLTIA) to identify the traffic impact of developing the LMG project which is a
mixed use development anchored by a furniture store and warehouse, south of SH 121,
between Plano Parkway and Spring Creek Parkway in the Colony, Texas.
The proposed development will consist of the anchor furniture store and warehouse, an
amusement park, convention center with hotel, office, convention center, amusement park,
residential, sporting goods superstore, and a mix of retail land uses. The anticipated land uses
and their sizes are summarized in Table 1 below and the preliminary site plan is included in
The development will be completed in two phases. Phase I will include the furniture store and
warehouse and is expected to be completed by 2015. Phase II will include the other land uses
on the site. This report assumed Phases I and II are implemented by 2015 in order to
determine the ultimate design for the surrounding roadway network.
This report documents the PLTIA for the proposed development. The analysis was designed to
meet the requirements of the City of The Colony, as well as conducted in accordance with the
guidelines from the Institute of Transportation Engineers. The study will present the expected
trip generation from the site, study the existing and future roadway system with and without
LMG Mixed‐Use Development Planning Level Traffic Impact Analysis
the proposed development, and mitigate any deficiencies found in the existing and future
roadway system that are caused by future growth that is expected without the development or
from the site. If the impacts cannot be mitigated using conventional capacity enhancements,
various demand and supply side alternatives will be provided for mitigating traffic impacts of
the proposed development. The following steps were executed to complete the analysis:
 Analysis of the existing roadway system;
 Analysis of future roadway system without the site in the years 2015 and 2020;
 Mitigation of any potential deficiencies in the future roadway systems;
 Development of traffic generated from the proposed development;
 Distribution of traffic from the proposed development onto the future roadway system;
Analysis of the future roadway system with the site in the years 2015 and 2020;
 Summarize the study results in a PLTIA report.
LMG Mixed‐Use Development Planning Level Traffic Impact Analysis
The proposed site for the mixed‐use development is located south of SH 121 between Plano
Parkway and Spring Creek Parkway in the Colony, Texas as shown in Figure 1.
Based on the location of the site and the City requirements, it was determined to study the
following interchanges/intersections that provide access to the proposed development:
 SH 121 and Spring Creek Parkway Interchange;
 S. Colony Boulevard at SH 121 southbound frontage road;
 Spring Creek Parkway and Headquarters Drive;
 Plano Parkway and Pizza Inn Driveway;
 Three future street intersections onto SH 121 northbound frontage road;
 Three future street intersections onto Plano Parkway; and,
 Site access onto SH 121 northbound frontage road.
Turning movement counts were collected at the existing intersections on a typical weekday for
the PM peak (4‐6 PM) and Saturday peak (1‐4 PM). The raw data is included in Appendix B.

A site visit was performed to inventory the existing conditions. The engineer conducting the
site visit collected intersection data from the study intersection including roadway geometry,
traffic control elements, and any other roadway elements that may impact the study network.
SH 121 (Sam Rayburn Tollway) is currently a six‐lane controlled access toll facility with three‐
lane one‐way frontage roads in both directions in the vicinity of the proposed development.
The posted speed limit on the mainlanes is currently 70 mph and on the frontage roads is 55
mph in the vicinity of the proposed development. The land uses along SH 121 near the site are
a combination of residential and retail.
Plano Parkway is currently a four‐lane median divided roadway in the vicinity of the site with a
40 mph posted speed limit between SH 121 and Tittle Drive, and 50 mph, posted speed limit
south of Tittle Drive. The City of Colony Major Thoroughfare Plan (2008) classified Plano
Parkway as a six‐lane divided major arterial with a 15’ median and a 55 mph median design
speed. The land uses along Plano Parkway in the vicinity of the site are mainly light industrial
Spring Creek Parkway is currently a six‐lane divided roadway in the vicinity of the site with a 45
mph posted speed limit, south of SH 121. The Collin County Major Thoroughfare Plan classifies
Spring Creek Parkway as a six‐lane divided principal arterial, south of SH 121. The land uses
along Spring Creek Parkway in the vicinity of the site are mainly residential and vacant tracts.
Legacy Drive is currently a six‐lane divided roadway east of SH 121 and a four‐lane divided
roadway west of SH 121. The Collin County Major Thoroughfare Plan classifies Legacy Drive as a
six‐lane divided principal arterial. The land uses along Legacy drive in the vicinity of the site are
The interchanges of SH 121 at Plano Parkway/Paige Road, SH 121 at Spring Creek Parkway, and
SH 121 at Legacy Drive are currently signalized. The intersection of Plano Parkway and Tittle

signal improvements, and roadway improvements within the street right‐of‐way. This project is

Synchro™ version 7 was used to create a model of the existing roadways and perform capacity
analyses of the study intersections. The capacity analysis software in Synchro™ is based on the
Transportation Research Board’s Highway Capacity Manual (HCM), 2000. The HCM is a
nationally recognized standard for performing capacity analyses.
Capacity analyses are evaluated based on a level of service that ranges from A (excellent) to F
(poor). Levels of service A through D are generally considered acceptable in urban
environments and levels of service E and F are considered unacceptable. City of The Colony
considers levels of service A through C acceptable and levels of service D through F
unacceptable, which will be the benchmark used for this study.
The analysis for signalized intersections and all‐way STOP controlled intersections provide a
level of service (LOS) for the entire intersection, an average for each approach (i.e. northbound,
southbound, etc), and a LOS for each movement (i.e. northbound left turn, northbound thru,
etc). The LOS is based on average control delay as detailed in the HCM. This report will use the
intersection LOS to meet the requirements set by the City.
Two‐way STOP controlled intersections/side street STOP controlled intersections provide a LOS
for each side street movement and an overall LOS for each side street approach. The main
street is assumed to have a LOS A since it does not stop, and therefore has no delay. The HCM
does not detail how to calculate the LOS for the entire intersection; therefore Synchro™ created
a measurement standard, the Intersection Capacity Utilization (ICU). Often the side street
approaches will receive a low LOS even though there are only a few cars waiting to enter the
main street. Therefore, this report will consider the anticipated queue length as reported in the
The level of service thresholds in the Highway Capacity Manual for signalized intersections and

The future background analysis considers what the intersection level of service will be without
the planned development. To determine what the future roadway traffic will be by the year
the site is occupied, two elements of growth must be considered. The first element is
background growth, which is caused from development in surrounding areas. The second
element is background development, which is caused by any known developments that will be
occupied between now and the time this development is completed.

As can be seen from Table 12, the interchanges of SH 121 at Plano Parkway/Paige Road and SH
121 at Spring Creek Parkway, as well as the intersections of SH 121 SBFR at South Colony
Boulevard and Spring Creek Parkway at Headquarters Drive are all expected to operate at an
unacceptable level of service during at least one peak period. The addition of the site traffic at
the two interchanges mentioned above, which serve as the main access points to the site result
in a significant increase in traffic at these interchanges. The U‐turn volumes at the SH 121
southbound frontage road at Paige Road and at SH 121 northbound frontage road and Spring
Creek Parkway both exceed 2,200 vehicles per hour. This results in excessively long queuing of
approximately half mile on the frontage roads at these interchanges. In addition the heavy left‐
turn volumes also result in significant delay for all approaches at these interchanges.
Conventional capacity enhancements such as lane additions, signal timing, and signal phasing
changes are not expected to improve operations at these interchanges to acceptable levels.

3. In addition to the demand level mitigation measures identified above, an additional

Parkway. The spacing between the intersections and the exiting ramp configuration

SH 121. Construction of an interchange was therefore assumed as a mitigation measure

LMG Mixed‐Use Development Planning Level Traffic Impact Analysis
Graham Associates has retained Savant Group, Inc. (SGI) to prepare a planning level traffic
impact analysis (PLTIA) to identify the traffic impact of developing the LMG project. The project
is a mixed use development anchored by a furniture store and warehouse, south of SH 121,
between Plano Parkway and Spring Creek Parkway in the Colony, Texas. Based on the analysis
conducted for this PLTIA, the interchanges of SH 121 at Plano Parkway/Paige Road and SH 121
at Spring Creek Parkway will have a significant addition of traffic as a result of the development
and conventional capacity enhancements such as turn lane additions and signal timing/phasing
optimization will not improve traffic to acceptable levels. Additional demand and supply side
mitigation measures are recommended to provide access to the site and mitigate the impact of
the site traffic on area roadways. These mitigation measures include:
1. Managing demand to the site attraction using Intelligent Transportation Systems (ITS)
and other information strategies. The ITS systems can include Dynamic Message Signs
on SH 121 to direct regional customers to alternate routes such as the Dallas North
Tollway. Information can also be provided to customers by means of website,
cellphones, etc. For the purpose of this planning level study, it was assumed that
approximately 30% of customers can be rerouted to access the site from entry points
2. The heavy westbound to southbound left‐turn at Spring Creek and the SH 121
northbound frontage road can be mitigated by placing dynamic message signs along
Spring Creek Parkway to inform drivers of the excessive delay for this movement and
encouraging drivers to reroute by making a right turn onto the frontage road and
making a u‐turn at Legacy Drive to access southbound SH 121. Additionally site traffic
can be prohibited from making a northbound left‐turn movement at Spring Creek
Parkway and Headquarters Drive and be rerouted to go straight onto Headquarters and
make a left onto a local roadway to access the frontage road. For this analysis, it was
assumed that approximately 25% of background traffic will divert to Legacy Drive and
exiting site traffic will be prohibited from make a left‐turn movement at Spring Creek
3. In addition to the demand level mitigation measures identified above, an additional
access point is recommended along SH 121 between Spring Creek Parkway and Plano
Parkway. The spacing between the intersections and the exiting ramp configuration
make S. Colony Boulevard a potential candidate for construction of an interchange along
SH 121. Construction of an interchange was therefore assumed as a mitigation measure
to relieve the Plano Parkway and Spring Creek Interchanges along SH 121.
